<TEXT>
the late gwendolyn cafritz philanthropist and 
famed washington partygiver reportedly has asked in her will that 
her landmark home become the secretary of states official residence 
the washington post reported in wednesdays editions that the 
request was confirmed by former secretary of state william rogers 
an executor of mrs cafritzs will and by martin atlas executive 
vice president of the morris and gwendolyn d cafritz foundation 
mrs cafritz died nov 29 at age 78 and her husband died in 1964 
a december 1987 appropriations bill for the state department 
prohibits the federal agency from acquiring an official residence 
for the secretary of state 
however secretary of state george shultz has said repeatedly 
that an official residence should be established for the secretary 
of state because of the security requirements for protecting the 
secretary as well as foreign guests 
shultz has said the government could save money by establishing 
an official secretarys house because the department has estimated 
it costs 500000 to make each private house secure for the 
secretary 
the post reported that mrs cafritz left her 14608squarefoot 
1938 art moderne house and its property to the cafritz foundation 
which is charged with carrying out her wishes 
rogers was quoted as saying that if the house cannot be used for 
the secretary of state mrs cafritz had suggested it could be used 
as an annex to blair house for visiting heads of state or for art 
scholars 
mrs cafritz was known for decades as one of washingtons premier 
partygivers hosting lavish gatherings for guests ranging from the 
duke and duchess of windsor to supreme court justices 
</TEXT>
