and inspection service said the agency has permitted use of the 
additives since september 1986 but it held off making a final 
decision until public comments had been submitted 
the substances are ascorbic acid erythorbic acid citric acid 
sodium ascorbate and sodium citrate which are used in fresh cuts of 
pork to maintain the meats color 
the use of these substances in the product does not pose a 
health risk crawford said fresh pork loses its color long 
before it becomes unsafe the color change makes the product 
unappealing 
product labels will identify the added substances and the reason 
for their use he said for example sprayed with a solution of 
water ascorbic acid and citric acid to maintain color 
