<TEXT>
when retired twa pilot dennis maloney 
picked up a newspaper he thought he might see a reference to a 
hijacking that occurred 20 years ago 
instead mondays headline twa flight to miami is hijacked 
carried him back to dec 11 1968 when he was the captain of 
another miamibound twa flight that was hijacked 
the two piracies took place 20 years apart almost to the hour 
both planes were boeing 727s and the flight numbers contained the 
same digits maloney said his was flight 496 sundays was flight 
469 
i couldnt believe it the same date the same time the same 
type of aircraft said maloney of suburban prairie village kan 
who retired 18 months ago after 23 years with twa i bet the 
chances arent 10 million to one of that happening 
sundays hijacking only the second involving a domestic us 
airliner in 2 years never made it to cuba the intended 
destination of the cuban exile who claimed to have a bomb 
authorities said the flight instead went to grand turk part of the 
british colony of turks and caicos islands southeast of the bahamas 
where the man was in custody pending extradition proceedings 
maloneys flight which originated in kansas city and stopped in 
st louis left nashville for miami when it was hijacked to havana 
it was the 19th us commercial airliner forced to cuba in 1968s 
wave of hijackings 
stories from 20 years ago described maloneys hijacker as a 
supercool gunman with a smiling female companion who appeared to be 
about six months pregnant among the 32 passengers and crew of seven 
were country singer tex ritter father of actor john ritter and pro 
golfer mason rudolph 
maloney 54 recalled there was early speculation the gunman 
might have been eldridge cleaver the black panther party activist 
who had disappeared in november 1968 to avoid arrest for violating 
parole 
but after being shown pictures of cleaver maloney and others 
said he was not the hijacker the gunman later was identified as a 
man named patterson a black panther who eventually ended up in 
algeria maloney said 
maloney said the hijacker grabbed a cabin attendant forced his 
way into the cockpit and ordered the crew to fly to cuba at gunpoint 
when the plane landed in havana between 200 and 300 cuban 
soldiers surrounded the plane maloney said the hijacker and his 
companion were taken off he was disarmed and they were marched 
away he said 
a diplomat from the swiss embassy arrived and interrogated the 
crew and passengers who were taken to a restaurant and fed before 
the passengers were taken to another airport and flown back to the 
united states 
maloney and his crew flew out of havana to miami that evening 
we all lived through it maloney said there was no 
problem other than the delay the next morning i kiddingly said to 
one of the administrative guys at twa i promised the crew a week 
off with pay he said i hope youve got enough money to pay for 
it out of your own pocket 
later as the number of hijackings continued to grow it became a 
policy to allow crews paid leave after an incident maloney said 
