a poll shows fewer americans admit to 
drinking and driving today than three years ago and the national 
safety council is attributing part of the decrease to a fear of 
getting caught 
from 1985 to 1988 the percentage of americans who said they 
drove after consuming alcohol fell from 37 percent to 28 percent 
according to the poll conducted by the roper organization for the 
allindustry research advisory council 
what were seeing is that the state laws are having some 
effect said david unnewehr research manager of the council 
based here west of chicago 
of those who said they are drinking and driving less 36 
percent said it was because of awareness of tougher laws and 
fines unnewehr said monday 
his group was established by the insurance industry to do 
research in policy areas affecting risk and insurance 
al lauersdorf alcohol programs administrator for the national 
safety council said the perception is there that their chances 
of being caught are greater and thats contributing to a decrease 
as a result greater numbers of people either do not drink when 
they are planning to drive or make other arrangements for 
transportation he said 
the designated driver concept where one person drinks soda or 
coffee or nothing has taken root across the country especially 
where mass transit is not an option said lauersdorf 
the increase of the drinking age to 21 throughout the country 
has cut a lot of drinking by younger people 
drivers between ages 18 and 34 a group more likely to drink and 
drive were mostly responsible for the decline unnewehr said 
the percentage of people from 18 to 24 drinking and driving 
dropped from 48 percent in 1985 to 31 percent in 1988 the poll 
showed among those 25 to 29 the number went from 53 percent in 1985 
to 39 percent this year 
for those ages 30 to 34 the percentage who said they drink and 
drive decreased from 51 percent to 33 percent 
the poll showed that 37 percent of men and 20 percent of women 
said they drove after drinking in 1985 the figures were 45 percent 
for men and 29 percent for women 
in the midwest 33 percent said they drove after drinking 
compared with 32 percent in the northeast 30 percent in the west 
and 21 percent in the south 
the research council commissioned similar studies in 1985 and 
1986 this years telephone survey of 1499 people around the 
country was conducted from june 418 and has an error margin of plus 
or minus 3 percentage points 
