the staff of the nuclear regulatory commission 
has cleared the way for the fivemember commission to consider an 
operating license for the long island lighting cos longdelayed 
shoreham nuclear power plant 
the staff on monday agreed with a september decision by the 
atomic safety licensing board which found that new york state and 
suffolk county had willfully obstructed the federal governments 
attempt to resolve the shoreham stalemate 
the 53 billion plant which was completed in 1984 has been 
unable to obtain an operating license because the state and local 
governments maintain that the surrounding area of densely populated 
long island could not be evacuated in an emergency 
if the commission accepts its staffs advice to uphold the 
boards recommendation that the local and state governments be 
dismissed from the shoreham proceedings no issues will remain to 
prevent a fullpower license for the plant said frank ingram a 
commission spokesman in washington 
ray golden a lilco spokesman said the utility was very 
pleased and optimistic that the nrc commissioners will act 
quickly on approval of a license 
brad ohearn a spokesman for suffolk county executive patrick 
halpin said the county will pursue vigorously with the full nrc 
board our contention that shoreham should not be operated because 
of evacuation concerns 
lilco has sought a full or 25 percentpower license for shoreham 
