mayor marion barry has canceled the citys 
annual downtown new years eve celebration citing a drug and crime 
epidemic and budget problems 
i think were in serious times now with the crime being what 
it is and the drug epidemic its no time to celebrate its a time 
to work hard and to pray he said in a radio interview monday 
night 
barry had boasted in 1986 that the nations capital celebration 
would surpass new york citys celebration in times square and become 
a major tourist attraction in the revitalized downtown pennsylvania 
avenue corridor 
the city began the street celebration in 1983 but the 1986 event 
sparked criticism after the strangled partially clad body of a high 
school student was found in a remote stairwell at the old post 
office pavilion 
that slaying along with 15 arrests and reports of fighting and 
bottle throwing led barry to change the entertainment at the bash 
emphasizing family fare 
in the past two years the city moved to ensure safety at the 
celebration by limiting alcohol sales adding police protection and 
changing the musical program 
last january officials said more than 100000 people attended 
the party far short of the estimated 1 million people who crowd 
times square 
as of today 347 homicides had been reported in the district of 
columbia so far this year police have estimated 60 percent are 
drugrelated the previous high was 287 in 1969 
barry has said the city faces a 150 million budget deficit he 
is scheduled to tell the city council on wednesday how he plans to 
solve the problem 
in the radio interview on whur barry said we want to emphasize 
family values and a number of other things and people ought to stay 
home those who are churchgoing people ought to go to watch 
services 
dc council member john a wilson whose ward includes downtown 
said he areed with barry 
i think hes also starting to prepare people for the 
difficulties were going to have next year because were going to 
have major financial problems said wilson chairman of the 
councils finance committee 
wilson added he doesnt want to be accused of wasting money 
right now 
