<TEXT>
on the seventh anniversary of the 
declaration of martial law and suppression of the solidarity trade 
movement students chanting solidarity pelted police with 
stones today and were answered with tear gas during a protest at 
warsaw university 
meanwhile the official press defended the imposition of martial 
law on dec 13 1981 by gen wojciech jaruzelski 
about 2000 students faced several hundred shieldcarrying 
helmeted police today at the gates of warsaw university along one of 
the citys main thouroughfares 
students hoisted banners saying solidarity and there is no 
freedom without solidarity and threw stones at the police from 
behind the walls of the campus police answered with canisters of 
tear gas 
at least three people were detained according to zuzanna 
dabrowska a student activist 
in a commentary on martial law the communist party daily trybuna 
ludu said one can remember dec 13th for years with a measure of 
bitterness and divisions one can open the healing wounds anew 
on that sunday morning in 1981 poles awoke to find tanks in the 
streets martial music playing on the radio and thousands of 
solidarity members rounded up and interned 
the army put an overnight end to the legal operation of 
solidarity a 10 millionmember social movement that had electrified 
the country for 15 months solidarity was at first suspended then 
legally banned in october 1982 
little bloodshed accompanied the imposition of martial law but 
nine coal miners were killed during a strike at the wujek mine near 
katowice on dec 16 1981 no other casualties were reported 
the anniversary cannot be an occasion for celebrations but 
can and should be a cause for reflection said trybuna ludu 
a government statement published in most newspapers today said 
the decision to impose martial law not only helped to prevent 
national catastrophe but to defend this reformatory process from 
those who often without being fully aware of it were preparing a 
tragic conclusion to it 
dictated by a supreme necessity the events of dec 13 1981 
did not stop the process of democratization and broad reforms 
under conditions of order not anarchy businesslike discussion not 
sterile disputes the sense of socialist renewal was restored 
alluding to solidarity and others in the opposition the 
statement said the communist partys offer for national 
reconciliation has not always been accepted 
some circles continue to stand aside from talks distrustfully 
or reluctantly viewing a proposal to assume coresponsibility for 
state affairs 
solidarity although still illegal has been increasingly 
tolerated by authorities who have been hoping to lure its leader 
lech walesa to discussions on polands future but the proposed 
talks with the government have stalled with walesa insisting he 
first wants a signal that authorities are willing to legalize his 
union 
the union demonstrated it has a strong following after leading 
two waves of strikes in 1988 
on nov 30 authorities allowed walesa to participate in a 
