<TEXT>
a former wrightpatterson air force base 
radiation safety officer was placed on probation by a federal judge 
tuesday on a charge that stemmed from a 1986 spill of radioactive 
material at the base 
us district judge walter rice ordered james w lewis 62 of 
enon to serve two years probation on a charge of illegally 
possessing highly radioactive americium 
rice also ordered lewis to pay 50 to a victims compensation 
fund and to perform 200 hours of community service 
rice said he believed lewis was guilty mainly of a lapse in 
judgment 
he is not a criminal said rice he is a good decent man 
lewis pleaded guilty to a charge of knowingly possessing a 
quantity of unsealed radioactive americium that was not authorized 
by the nuclear regulatory commission prosecutors dropped a charge 
of making a false statement to the nrc 
lewis could have been sentenced to two years in prison fined as 
much as 250000 and ordered to pay full restitution 
according to a statement submitted to the court lewis on june 
15 1978 received a drum from newark jeweler jc haynes that 
contained lab waste contaminated with what lewis thought were trace 
amounts of americium lewis agreed to accept and transport the drum 
to wrightpatterson where it was stored with other radioactive 
materials at the base 
no one was injured in the spill of the radioactive powder but a 
radiological safety officer said tests showed that one air force 
officer inhaled a small quantity of the material the spill resulted 
in a 1 million cleanup 
the powder initially leaked from an unlabeled barrel at the base 
while four workers were taking inventory sept 18 1986 the powder 
is not considered dangerous to the skin but can cause cancer if it 
is swallowed or inhaled experts say 
the workers later washed themselves under a spigot at a boy scout 
camp at the base air force officials said there was no 
contamination there but as a precaution offered to test hundreds of 
boy scouts who had camped there 
a second spill of americium occurred oct 6 1986 
revelations of the spill one year after it happened touched off 
allegations of a coverup by air force officials and prompted a us 
senate governmental affairs committee hearing near the base 
