dcolo a member of the house armed services committee and a 
frequent critic of reagan administration defense policies head the 
advisory board of the cambridge massbased research center 
mrs schroeder who released the study at a news conference 
noted the announcement last week by soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev that the soviet union was cutting its armed forces by 10 
percent worldwide some of the reductions will be in eastern europe 
and the soviet forces also will be restructured to make them 
defensive rather than offensive gorbachev said 
as we face the largest budget deficit in our nations history 
mr gorbachevs initiative gives us the opportunity to cut our 
defense budget without endangering our national security mrs 
schroeder said 
our european allies must still face up to new 
responsibilities she added 
in the face of a new positive arms control climate and the 
emergence of western europe as a unified world trading entity our 
european allies must prepare themselves not only for this new role 
but for roles and responsibilities that come with being a global 
power she said 
the study proposed several responses to gorbachevs plan 
including 
an immediate confidencebuilding withdrawal of 5 percent of 
the active ground forces in central europe by both sides which 
would be 20000 soviet troops and 10000 us troops gorbachev had 
pledged to implement his reductions by 1991 
a pause in deployment of new shortrange nuclear weapons by nato 
and the soviet bloc mediumrange missiles are being eliminated by a 
ussoviet treaty signed a year ago but the pact doesnt affect 
weapons with socalled battlefield range 
movement to dominance by defense rather than offense in the 
military structure of each side one example would be a decrease in 
heavily armored forces including tanks and artillery because those 
forces normally are employed in attack 
a prime focus of arms control efforts should be the withdrawal of 
offensive weapons the study said 
one of the hurdles to be overcome is the belief by western 
leaders that nato forces already are at the minimum level despite 
the warsaw pact reductions the study said 
another potential problem it cited was the possibility that 
nato may be reluctant to break its morbid dependence on nuclear 
weapons even if progress in conventional arms negotiations 
undermines the present rationale for those weapons 
</TEXT>
