<TEXT>
earthquake survivors shivered in freezing weather 
with little shelter tuesday and foreign medical experts said rescue 
efforts should focus on the living because it is too late to save 
people still trapped 
six days after the earthquake razed northern armenia the 
official death toll climbed to 55000 and the number of injured 
reached 13000 soviet foreign ministry spokesman gennady gerasimov 
told a news briefing 
one of our most urgent tasks is to rescue those people who are 
alive gerasimov said about 5400 people have been pulled from 
wrecked buildings since the earthquake and the number still trapped 
is not known 
but two foreign doctors involved in the relief effort said 
resources must be devoted to saving those who are known to have 
survived 
dr bernard mankikian visited the region around spitak as part of 
a relief team from the french branch of medecins du monde doctors 
without borders which returned to paris on tuesday 
spitak small town near the epicenter of wednesdays quake was 
almost totally destroyed 
they survivors are almost totally isolated in the cold he 
said people are staying close to their homes without shelter or 
access to aid that is available in the bigger towns they cannot 
stay like this and survive he said 
relief workers with blankets warm clothes and tents have yet to 
reach survivors in small isolated villages around the mountainous 
countryside near spitak 
soviet television tuesday showed rows of tents set up near the 
ruins of the city of stepanovan to the northeast the commentator 
said there are not enough tents 
a commission headed by prime minister nikolai ryzhkov has ordered 
soviet relief workers to ensure that warm clothes blankets and 
tents reach rural areas the official news agency tass reported 
tuesday 
it was pointed out that the state agroindustrial committees of 
armenia and the soviet union had displayed perplexity and lack of 
organization at first tass said tuesday the situation began to 
change after resolute measures were taken yesterday 
the soviet meteorological center in moscow forecast continued 
freezing weather for the next several days trucks struggled to 
cross snowy mountain passes to bring in tents flown in by relief 
planes to outlying areas 
the communist youth newspaper komsomolskaya pravda said 60000 
tents have been sent to the disaster area but many people still 
were shivering around bonfires scattered among the ruins 
the collapsed villages are suffering especially from the 
disaster the newspaper said quoting helicopter capt sergei 
bobylev in one village 20 children died in the quake and now 
survivors are dying from cold the newspaper said 
survivors also have other tasks on their minds besides their own 
shelter and safety they are busy burying their relatives or 
searching for loved ones still buried under the rubble 
in the village of nalbanb with a prequake population of 4200 
residents have already buried 2800 of the dead associated press 
photographer morton hvaal reported after visiting the village on 
tuesday 
dr robert gale a bone marrow specialist who assisted the 
soviets following the chernobyl nuclear disaster in april 1986 said 
the medical effort must now focus on saving those who survived 
because it is too late to help those still buried 
we now consider the search and rescue phase as being over 
because there is very little hope of finding anyone alive said 
gale who arrived in yerevan on sunday and went straight to spitak 
in the long run well save more lives in yerevan by 
reinforcing the hospitals there gale said 
but one of mankikians colleagues patrick aeberhard said in 
paris that the cold actually could help trapped victims by slowing 
their metabolism and allowing them to live longer 
citing the experience of other earthquake disasters such as 
mexico city where people lived for up to two weeks buried in 
rubble ryzhkov pledged on monday to keep looking for survivors as 
long as it was possible to find anyone 
in his first public comment since he left the quake area health 
minister yevgeny chazov described the conditions faced by some of 
the 220 medical teams in armenia 
the first complex operations including amputations were carried 
out in the streets under the open air tass quoted chazov as saying 
when we arrived in the quakestricken area there was neither 
electric light nor communications there fires were raging the 
quake destroyed all hospitals seventy per cent of the medical 
personnel was killed chazov said 
