<TEXT>
a 50 percent pay increase for 2500 top federal 
officials was recommended tuesday by a presidential commission which 
said members of congress should quit pocketing fees from 
specialinterest groups in exchange for heftier checks from the 
taxpayers 
i think the pressure on congress to get rid of honoraria is 
going to be very strong said lloyd cutler chairman of the 
commission on executive legislative and judicial salaries after 
the panel unanimously adopted its recommendations in my view it 
will be irresistible 
the commission recommended that members of congress and federal 
district judges who now make 89500 a year be paid 135000 the 
house speaker would go from 115000 to 175000 and majority and 
minority leaders from 99500 to 155000 top executivebranch 
officials such as cabinet members would get boosts from their 
current 99500 to 155000 
the proposed pay increases officially will be forwarded on 
wednesday to president reagan who can then accept or modify the 
figures before sending his budget to congress on jan 9 
under the law unless both the house and senate vote to head off 
the pay increases they automatically will take effect 30 days 
later congressional supporters of the increases hope to avoid any 
votes although opponents are unlikely to let the clock expire 
without a fight 
the pay commission also said congress should act to give the 
president whose salary has been fixed at 200000 since 1969 a 
raise to about 350000 such an increase could not take effect 
until 1993 because of a constitutional prohibition on raising a 
presidents pay during his term 
commission members conceded that the recommended increases will 
appear huge to taxpayers but cutler noted that baseball players 
even 200hitting utility infielders receive more than a district 
court judge or a member of congress or a deputy secretary of state 
and they said the cost of the increase would be relatively small 
about 128 million overall in fiscal 1990 these numbers are 
probably no more than what gets spilled at the pentagon every day 
said cutler 
chief justice william h rehnquist said the panels action is 
bound to be encouraging to the nations federal judges the 
commissions salary recommendations would restore to those judges 
the cuts in real income which have been caused by inflation over the 
last 20 years 
not only the judges but everyone interested in attracting to 
the bench capable men and women for a lifetime of service will be 
well served if the president and congress follow these 
recommendations rehnquist said 
top federal workers buying power has declined 35 percent on 
average since 1969 when the salaries first were adjusted under the 
commissions recommendations tuesdays proposal was an attempt to 
play catchup with two decades of inflation 
it also was a way of tempting congress to wean itself from the 
burgeoning practice of seeking speaking fees from interest groups 
and giving lawmakers the political cover they need to accept a pay 
raise the selfstyled citizens lobby common cause noted that 
lawmakers had accepted a record 98 million in such fees in 1987 
the pay recommendations directly affect about 2500 top federal 
jobs and indirectly impact another 10000 highlevel positions 
where pay is tied to salaries in the top echelon 
in its report the commission cited testimony that top federal 
positions are going begging for talented people because of the huge 
discrepancy between government salaries and privatesector pay 
cutler noted that the average top executivebranch worker now 
stays on the job just 18 months they barely get to understand 
their jobs before they leave because of inadequate salaries he 
said cutler added that senior research posts at the national 
institutes of health have gone unfilled for 10 years because the 
government cant attract top talent he said 
but of all three branches the most appealing case is the case 
of the judges cutler said judges are leaving in droves to 
return to far more lucrative law practices soon theyll all be 
millionaire wall street lawyers you wont have blacks on the bench 
you wont have women on the bench 
the panel made it clear that it intended the raises to go 
handinhand with a ban on honoraria not only speaking fees but 
other ways in which specialinterest groups could funnel money to 
lawmakers to buy access and influence 
it is our devout intent that there be this quid pro quo said 
commission member and former sen thomas eagleton dmo we view 
that as an ample fulltime salary in return for which we expect 
congress will outlaw all forms of honoraria conceivable to man 
consumer advocate ralph nader called the pay recommendation a 
shameless salary grab and predicted a public revolt the public 
is saying you are freezing the minimum wage and asking for a pay 
increase top public officials already make several times the 
average working americans salary he said 
rep tom tauke riowa said he would oppose the pay increase and 
called on colleagues to scrap the law that lets such raises take 
effect without a vote 
house speaker jim wright dtexas who has publicly advocated 
doing away with honoraria will favor whatever salary level reagan 
proposes said an aide to the speaker 
rep tony coelho dcalif the majority whip predicted the pay 
raise will ultimately take effect the opportunity to beat up on 
this thing is great he said but the reality is that people 
with collegeage kids can no longer be involved in public service 
the american bar association embraced the commissions 
recommendations for the judiciary saying many of the men and 
women serving today on the federal bench are making extraordinary 
financial sacrifices in order to remain on the bench and many 
others who would aspire to the bench are finding the financial 
sacrifices too great 
the national taxpayers union said reagan should ignore these 
outrageous recommendations this scheme was designed to fool the 
voters and enrich the congress 
tuesdays recommendations were similar to those proposed by the 
commission in 1986 at that time reagan reduced the levels before 
submitting them to congress the senate voted to reject the pay 
raises but the house allowed the 30day clock to expire before 
voting and the increases took effect 
