<TEXT>
some of congress most visible and 
controversial perks the 1000 breakfast the 2000 lunch and the 
10000 allexpensespaid tours of defense plants came under fire 
tuesday from a presidential commission 
the panel while recommending 50 percent pay increases for top 
federal officials suggested that members of the house and senate 
honor their part of the bargain by dumping their honoraria 
the commission said members of congress should be paid 135000 
instead of 89500 but they should give up the speaking and writing 
fees that brought in a record 98 million in 1987 up 30 percent 
over 1986 
unlike bureaucrats and judges members of congress are free to 
use their positions to collect speaking fees most often from lobby 
groups and trade associations with a stake in a members votes in 
committee or on the floor 
the potential for abuse or the appearance of abuse is obvious 
to the public the salary commission said in a report to president 
reagan the only principled argument that can be made for the 
practice of accepting honoraria is that official salaries are too 
low 
this put the commission in line with longtime honoraria critics 
like fred wertheimer president of common cause the selfstyled 
citizens lobby 
the growing practice of accepting honoraria from special 
interests raises intolerable conflicts of interest and gravely 
undermines the integrity of congress and the public trust in 
government wertheimer said tuesday 
there is no limit on how much a member can make through 
honoraria the 1987 capitol hill champion rep dan rostenkowski 
the illinois democrat who heads the taxwriting ways and means 
committee pulled in 245000 
there are limits however on how much a member can keep the 
senate has a limit amounting to 40 percent of official salary or 
35800 the houses limit is 30 percent of salary or 26850 
there is a 2000 cap on a single honoraria payment 
to keep within the limit rostenkowski gave 219156 of his 1987 
honoraria earnings to various charities leaving 25844 for 
himself the senates top honoraria earner in 1987 minority leader 
bob dole rkan made 106050 on the speaking circuit gave 
80000 to charity and kept 26050 for himself neary 10000 less 
than he could have kept 
neither man nor any of their colleagues would suffer an earnings 
cut under the commissions plan a senator now keeping honoraria to 
the limit would be 9700 ahead of the current system if the pay 
goes to 135000 a house member at the limit would end up 18650 
ahead 
according to financial disclosure statements 87 senators 
received 31 million in honoraria in 1987 keeping 23 million or 
nearly 74 percent in the house 390 of the 435 members shared 667 
million and kept about 78 percent of it 524 million 
