<TEXT>
south africa cuba and angola signed a 
usmediated peace plan tuesday stipulating that southwest africa 
will become independent and 50000 cuban soldiers will leave angola 
westernbacked rebels fighting the government of angola were not 
included in the agreement which would end only foreign fighting 
there 
this will bring an end to international conflict in 
southwestern africa said chester crocker the us diplomat who 
was the agreements chief architect it is the end of a sad 
chapter in african history 
crocker assistant secretary of state for african affairs said 
the accord was achieved in large part through ussoviet 
cooperation 
crockers negotiations on southwest africa also known as 
namibia were a central element in the reagan administrations 
constructive engagement policy toward south africa which 
congress rejected in favor of sanctions 
applause by black african diplomats and officials interrupted 
foreign minister rf botha of south africa when he declared 
tuesday a new era has begun my government is removing racial 
discrimination we want to be accepted by our african brothers we 
need each other 
south africa clearly sees the agreement as a chance to improve an 
international image marred by its apartheid system of racial 
discrimination and end conflict that has cost hundreds of millions 
of dollars and killed hundreds of white soldiers 
botha signed for south africa in a ceremony attended by the congo 
president denis sassoungueso whose government has been host to 
several negotiating sessions meetings leading to the agreement 
began in may 
also signing the agreement tuesday were angolas military chief 
of staff antonio dos santos franca and ricardo alarcon quesada 
cuban deputy foreign minister alarcon said it begins a new era of 
peace 
in washington white house spokesman marlin fitzwater also hailed 
the pact 
we hope that this major diplomatic milestone in southern africa 
will be followed by renewed efforts to settle the internal conflict 
in angola through a process of national reconcilation and peaceful 
negotiation among angolans he said 
the agreement to be formalized in a treaty scheduled for signing 
dec 22 in new york does not end the civil war in angola but bars 
the involvement of south african and cuban forces 
prowestern guerrillas of the union for the total independence of 
angola or unita have fought the marxist government of angola since 
independence from portugal in 1975 
some african leaders have expressed hope the withdrawal of cuban 
and south african troops would lead to negotiations between angola 
and jonas savimbis unita rebels who have been supported by south 
africa and the united states 
south african military sources reported new fighting monday 
between angolan soldiers and unita 
whatever the course of angolas civil conflict the agreement if 
carried out successfully would end 22 years of sporadic bush 
warfare in namibia a territory rich in minerals that south africa 
has controlled since capturing it from germany in world war i 
the southwest african peoples organization which has been 
fighting south africa for control of namibia from bases inside 
angola welcomed the pact tuesday 
we are happy that at long last our people will be able to 
exercise their right of selfdetermination said spokesman hidipo 
hamutenya 
he said his groups forces in namibia will observe an informal 
ceasefire and fight only if provoked or cornered 
the league of nations gave south africa a mandate but the un 
general assembly withdrew it in 1966 and has tried since then to get 
the south africans out 
botha said implementation of a un independence plan will begin 
april 1 and elections are expected seven months later 
speaking to reporters on the flight from johannesburg to the 
congolese capital he also said the plan calls for 3000 cuban 
troops to leave angola before april 1 all 50000 are to be out 
within 27 months 
about half the cubans are expected to be withdrawn by the time 
elections are held in southwest africa about nov 1 1989 most of 
those remaining are to move north at least 350 miles from the 
namibian frontier 
prisoners of war are to be exchanged and a joint commission will 
be formed to resolve disputes cuba and angola are to negotiate an 
agreement with javier perez de cuellar the un secretarygeneral 
for verification of the cuban withdrawal 
politicians in windhoek the territorial capital reacted with 
wary approval 
andreas shipanga a black namibian who is cabinet chairman in the 
transitional government said of the day when the independence plan 
is supposed to go into effect april fools day i dont trust 
that date but well accept it 
