<TEXT>
the national commission on working women on 
tuesday honored the broadcast industry for making the 1980s a 
decade of progress for women on television 
our report shows progress in the treatment of women on 
television over the past ten years and because of that the 
networks get a pat on the back said sally streenland who wrote a 
study released by the commission entitled ten years in prime time 
an analysis of the image of women on entertainment television 
19791988 
the report citing the expansion and diversification of female 
characters in primetime television examined the portrayal of women 
and compared the fictional panorama with the profile of reallife 
women during the decade 
the 1980s mark a decade of progress for women on television 
their portrayals have become more diverse and for the most part 
more truetolife the report concluded 
the commission also presented three new milestone awards to 
people who have made outstanding contributions to advancing the 
role of women through the media the recipients were abc news 
senior correspondent carole simpson cagney amp lacey tv series 
actresses sharon gless and tyne daly and executive producer barney 
rosenzweig and national public radio 
the studys examination of the 25 top nielsen rated shows from 
1979 to the 1988 fall season revealed that as the percentage of 
working mothers increased in the workplace so did their percentage 
in tv portrayals 
the study showed that 60 percent of tvs female characters worked 
in 1979 threequarters of the tv women were single 10 percent were 
single mothers and 5 percent were married mothers 
by 1987 75 percent of the women americans watched on television 
worked onefourth were single 15 percent single mothers and 20 
percent married mothers according to the report 
meanwhile 1987 population statistics from the us census bureau 
showed 56 percent of all women were in the labor force 25 percent 
have never been married 30 percent are married working mothers 10 
percent are single mothers and 25 percent are homemakers 
the pat on the back is a somewhat soft one because despite the 
growing diversity in these areas television has been fascinated 
with wealth for much of the 80s said streenland citing 
nighttime soap operas there has not been that diversity 
economically 
streenlands study showed tv painting a much rosier picture than 
actually existed of the types of employment women had 
in 1979 more than 40 percent of televisions women were employed 
in clerical or service jobs with a corresponding percentage in 
professional jobs by 1987 only 23 percent of the women on tv had 
the lower skilled jobs and more than half had professional careers 
the real life portrait was almost exactly reversed with 47 
percent in clerical and service occupations and only 24 percent 
working in professional or managerial jobs in the real world 
twothirds of us women earn 15000 or less only 1 percent earn 
more than 50000 
the report also showed the percentage of black women on tv almost 
tripled during the period studied in 1979 there was only one black 
female character representing 8 percent of the women on tv that 
year by 1987 22 percent of the women on tv were black 
but only 2 percent of tvs women in 1987 were hispanic and there 
were no asian or other minority women depicted in reality 77 
percent of women in the united states are white 125 percent are 
black 75 percent are hispanic and 3 percent are other minority 
women 
the commission also presented its annual alice awards to 
actresses producers and journalists for excellence in portraying 
working womens issues in radio and television at a luncheon 
ceremony tuesday 
since joining the commission and the broadcast awards program 
i more perfectly understand the importance of portraying reallife 
situations said actress linda lavin whose waitress character 
gave the commissions award its name i think twice about the 
roles i take and the programs i produce 
carole simpson who won one of the milestone awards said i 
would have to say that entertainment has moved along further than 
news has it is still astounding to me that at my network there 
are 115 correspondents and only 15 of them are women that there is 
no woman anchoring the news on a daily broadcast 
