<TEXT>
the transportation department is reviewing a 
request by one of the countrys major railroads to eliminate random 
tests as part of a drug testing program for railroad workers 
officials said tuesday 
csx transportation inc filed a petition with the federal 
railroad administration this week asking that a railroad not be 
required to conduct random drug tests if it already has a proven 
drug testing program under way 
the dot maintains that random testing is an integral part of an 
effective drug testing program for transportation workers involved 
in safety related jobs 
but csx one of the nations largest railroad companies said 
random testing is at best an untried experiment and that there 
are other methods to combat drug abuse problem in the railroad 
industry 
fra administrator john riley said the petition will be given 
full and fair consideration as will any other suggestion for a 
modification of the drug testing requirements that were announced 
last month 
unions representing 200000 railroad workers sued tuesday in 
federal court in san francisco challenging the drug testing program 
in the railroad industry 
the suit contends random drug testing without suspicion of 
current drug use violates constitutional standards for searches it 
also contends the fra has no legal authority to order random testing 
a suit by the unions in the same court resulted in a ruling by 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals in february prohibiting 
postaccident drug testing by railroads without reasonable suspicion 
of individual drug use that case was one of two drug testing cases 
argued before the supreme court last month no ruling has been 
issued 
the transportation department on nov 14 said millions of 
transportation workers including railroad workers will be subject 
to a broad range of drug tests beginning in december 1989 
the random tests have been strongly opposed by labor but most 
transportation companies have endorsed them as being necessary 
during a series of hearings on drug testing csx was the only 
railroad that opposed random testing 
in its petition csx said it does not believe the evidence 
supports random drug testing as the most effective means of 
combating drug abuse in the industry 
csx asked that a railroad be exempted from the random testing 
requirement if it can show that its existing drug testing program 
works as well or better than the expectations of random drug 
testing 
random testing in the railroad industry is at best an untried 
experiment with many admitted unknowns csx said in a statement 
that belief is based not on supposition but on the railroads 
actual experience 
