<TEXT>
the district of columbia council on tuesday 
passed congressionally mandated laws allowing insurance companies to 
test health insurance applicants for the aids virus 
the council enacted the insurance law despite a raucous angry 
protest from about 250 gay advocates who disrupted the councils 
proceedings about 50 were removed from the councils chambers and 
five were arrested on disorderly conduct charges police said 
the aids testing measure repealed a 1986 ban on such testing that 
the council had enacted in an effort to head off discrimination 
against homosexuals 
in response to the 1986 ordinance insurance companies in the 
district had simply stopped writing new health care plans and 
congress had threatened to cut off its 537 million payment to the 
city for the fiscal year that began oct 1 if the law was not 
changed 
the council also replaced its requirement that all city employees 
live in the city with a plan that gives preference to city residents 
for all city jobs congress pushed that system on the city after 
reports that the police department and city agencies were having 
trouble recruiting workers from the citys applicant pool 
under the plan residents exercising the preference option on 
their applications would be required to live in the city for five 
years at which point they would be free to move to the maryland or 
virginia suburbs 
the council also passed a law guaranteeing that city buildings 
will be opened to homeless persons if all the citys shelters are 
filled on nights when the temperature drops below 25 degrees 
fahrenheit 
