<TEXT>
theres a moment in clint eastwoods movie 
bird when the great jazzman charlie parker stands on a 
blackened paris stage after finishing a concert consuming massive 
doses of applause and sniffing a longstemmed red rose 
he was something of a god to jazz zealots but perhaps the 
tortured musical genius never really got a chance to wake up and 
smell the roses he mutilated his life with drugs and alcohol and 
died at the age of 34 in 1955 
eastwood who has loved jazz since his childhood and who always 
wanted to film a portrait of parker attempts to harness the birds 
creative spirit and all the creative juices of that time a time 
when bebop came to fore and brought jazz into the modern age at the 
same time it pokes into the underbelly of the jazz world with its 
stark portrayal of drugs alcohol debauchery 
his life was obviously filled with many excesses sort of a 
dichotomy eastwood says how a person who can be so brilliant 
and who spent hours and hours to become as great as he did and have 
that kind of discipline could not in any other part of his life 
that was always a wonder to me 
but i wanted a movie where you root for him i just wanted 
to explore the fact that he was brilliant and innovative and the 
other just became a part of his life 
eastwood even films bird in a dark brownish hue 
most of the jazz world is nocturnal he says tv 
unfortunately has shown a whole generation that flat light is the 
only way i dont like flat light i like the feel of the movie i 
like to look into a film instead of having it look out at you i 
approached the color of it in terms of black and white 
forest whitaker good morning vietnam platoon is 
gentle yet fierce playful yet obsessed in his role as parker for 
which he was awarded the best actor prize at the cannes film 
festival it was well deserved for a stunning performance that even 
captures the hunched body stances once assumed by the musician as he 
performed as chan parker diane venora ironweed fx 
finds the right balance between free spirit and strong loving wife 
who battles her husbands philandering and personal demons and at 
the same time champions his work and wellbeing 
 
bird followed the success of last years round midnight 
the story of an expatriate sax player in paris tenor saxophone 
great dexter gordon who once worked with parker received an 
academy award nomination for his role as the tragic dale turner 
though based loosely on the late jazz musician bud powell bertrand 
taverniers movie is a universal story of jazz artists who fled 
bigotry and rough times in america for the allure of paris and 
amsterdam during the 1940s 50s and 60s 
paris blues martin ritts 1961 jazz movie starring paul 
newman and sidney poitier takes a more romantic hollywood 
approach the late duke ellington received an oscar nomination for 
his score 
in bird lenny niehaus did the score which isolates parkers 
original playing of laura april in paris ornithology 
parkers mood and other jazz tunes and remixes his recorded 
solos with contemporary musicians including bassist ron carter 
trumpeter john faddis pianists walter davis jr and barry harris 
jazz purists have been rankled by the soundtrack which they say is 
technically excellent but misses the interplay between parker and 
his sidemen 
but eastwood defends his decision if youre going to do a film 
and have stereophonic sound you need to record well charlie never 
had the opportunity to do stereophonic sound 
charlie parker was born in kansas city and took up first 
baritone and then alto sax while still in high school which he left 
at the age of 14 so he could study such greats as lester young and 
count basie in the local clubs he soon found himself in new york 
where a young trumpet player named dizzy gillespie was all the rage 
with thelonious monk and bud powell on piano kenny clarke on 
drums and later a young miles davis on trumpet parker and gillespie 
helped define and create a new musical venture in jazz bebop 
parker whose nickname was yardbird and shortened to bird 
stumbled into the lost world of night life but even with the 
debiliation of drugs and alcohol he never failed to solve musical 
problems and invent new directions 
there have been no great harmonic changes in jazz since charlie 
and dizzy eastwood says 
and then he muses what musical levels would parker have reached 
today had he lived it would be interesting the actorfilmmaker 
says 
