<TEXT>
for farmers across america 1988 was a 3d year drought 
destruction and despair 
the nation suffered through one of the worst dry spells in a 
halfcentury since the days of the dust bowl as sunny skies 
created clouds of doom for thousands of farmers who watched their 
crops and hopes shrivel in blistering tripledigit heat 
it was a year when farmers prayed and indians danced for rain 
when the mighty mississippi stopped its easy rolling and crop seeds 
started blowing when the country sizzled while the fourth of july 
fizzled because fireworks celebrations were canceled for fear of 
igniting grass fires 
but the drought brought prosperity too for rail carriers whose 
business picked up when barge traffic slowed down for auction 
houses flooded with livestock because ranchers were short on feed 
and for farmers lucky enough to have surpluses or to live in areas 
blessed with rain 
in fact although losses climbed into the billions of dollars and 
thousands of acres of crops were lost the drought was not the total 
disaster some had feared 
prices were up we had some of last years crop in the bin to 
sell said jim nichols minnesotas agriculture commissioner 
thats what saved us it didnt have to anything to do with 
the crop we harvested this year 
and with billions of dollars of federal aid and late rains 
most farmers have fared much better than they would have 
otherwise said jim vertrees an agriculture department economist 
but thats not to say farmers arent hurting he added corn 
production fell by 34 percent from last years bumper crop while 
soybeans dropped 21 percent and spring wheat 54 percent vertrees 
said 
the council of economic advisers has estimated crop losses at 
about 13 billion in 1982 prices vertrees said 
despite those gloomy numbers the agriculture department citing 
higher commodity prices inventory and only moderate drops in 
government subsidies has predicted net cash income the amount of 
money farmers have to spend during the year to be close to 1987s 
record 571 billion 
but many states were hit hard in sparsely populated north 
dakota for example the estimated total loss including the impact 
on nonagricultural business dependent on the farm economy is a 
whopping 22 billion even with federal aid said arlen leholm a 
north dakota state university extension economist 
and leholm noted the drought came at a time when many farmers 
were just digging out from the agricultural crisis of the early 
1980s land prices were climbing slowly livestock prices were up 
there was a general feeling of optimism he said they had 
feelings of euphoria they felt maybe i can see the light at the 
end of the tunnel then it turned out to be a train 
from may through july the critical growing season 
precipitation was at record lows in seven states from montana to 
mississippi and at its secondlowest levels ever in six other 
states from georgia to north dakota 
signs of trouble surfaced early in may ranchers in the parched 
texas prairies were burning thorns off prickly cactuses to feed to 
cattle from san francisco to atlanta residents were asked to 
reduce water consumption 
it reached different people at different times said neil 
harl an economics professor at iowa state university it became 
increasingly clear as temperatures started to rise by early june we 
had a serious problem 
heat records fell in city after city aggravating the bonedry 
conditions water levels shrunk by june more than a thousand 
barges were stranded in the shrunken mississippi wind erosion had 
damaged millions of acres in the great plains fish were dying in 
wisconsin streams and wells were drained in nebraska 
as summer began anxious farmers fought to keep their animals 
from starving and watched their normally kneehigh corn stunted at 
anklelevel 
although rain fell in some spots hints of relief didnt come 
until august when president reagan signed a 39 billion drought 
aid package that provides disaster payments to those who harvested 
less than 65 percent of their normal production 
it was one of two silver linings we were not anticipating 
congress would be as generous or that crops would be as resilient as 
they were harl said 
farmers also benefited from an additional 3 billion in emergency 
aid feed assistance and crop insurance and relaxed standards 
that allowed haying or grazing on land normally exempt from such 
uses 
by fall the farmers home administration also had declared 1489 
counties eligible for emergency disaster loans including 13 entire 
states vertrees said 
still it was a bitter harvest for farmers facing another season 
with little moisture in the ground and less grain in the bin 
were in a situation where its going to take above average 
rainfalls to have an average crop said bruce bullock an 
agricultural economist at the university of missouri its a 
little premature to say the drought is totally behind us 
</TEXT>
