spending rose about 67 percent 
he said 1989 will also be the first time since 1975 that ad 
spending failed to exceed the expected 68 percent growth including 
inflation that many economists forecast for the economy next year 
meanwhile foreign ad spending was projected to exceed us ad 
spending for the first time this year and is expected to widen its 
lead next year 
coen said foreign ad spending grew 18 percent to about 1214 
billion in 1988 compared with spending of 1183 billion in the 
united states 
next year he said while us ad spending rises to 1256 
billion foreign ad spending should rise 12 percent to 136 billion 
in the us market coen blamed the sluggish pace of local ad 
spending growth on turmoil in retail marketing partly to recent 
acquisitions and restructuring in the retail business he said the 
activity has left less money available for spending on local 
advertising 
he also said the volume of classified advertising in newspapers 
appears to have flattened out after several years of rapid growth 
he cited a decline in real estate activity due to higher mortgage 
rates and slower growth in helpwanted advertising 
he expects local ad spending will reach 553 billion next year 
coen said he expects 1989 spending on the national broadcast 
media will rise 45 percent to 212 billion national print 
spending will be up 58 percent to 102 billion and other national 
ad spending such as the fastgrowing direct mail will be up 78 
percent to 389 billion 
spending on network television will be flat because of the 
absence of an estimated 1 billion in spending related to the 
olympics but cable and syndicated television should have 
doubledigit gains again coen said 
national ad spending in newspapers should be flat while spending 
in magazines may fall back particularly if automotive and toiletry 
sectors scale back the growth in their ad spending 
coen was more optimistic about his longerterm outlook for ad 
spending 
the correction in overexpanded ad spending of the early 1980s 
has been completed and most budgets are back in line with other 
operating costs he said 
