<DOCNO> AP881213-0256 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the deficit in the broadest measure of us 
trade narrowed to 309 billion from july through september the 
smallest imbalance in three years the government reported today 
the commerce department said americas deficit in its current 
account fell by 84 percent from a second quarter level of 337 
billion as us manufacturers continued to enjoy a boom in export 
sales 
the current account is the most important trade statistic because 
it measures not only trade in merchandise but also trade in 
investments and other services the third quarter deficit was the 
smallest imbalance since a 276 billion deficit in the third 
quarter of 1985 
half of the improvement in the latest quarter came from a 56 
percent decline in the merchandise deficit as exports of both 
agricultural products and merchandise increased 
also showing improvement was the investment and services 
category which had posted an 837 million deficit in the second 
quarter the first deficit in this category in 30 years for the 
third quarter this had returned to a surplus of 757 million 
the current account also known as the countrys balance of 
payments hit a record deficit of 15396 billion in 1987 
in the first nine months of this year the current account 
deficit has been running at an annual rate of 13542 billion 
deficit while this is a significant improvement it still leaves 
the current account deficit at a high level 
this figure is important because it translates into the amount of 
money foreigners have to lend or invest in the united states the 
string of deteriorating current account deficits beginning in 1982 
has meant the united states has gone from being the worlds largest 
creditor nation to the largest debtor country as americans have 
handed over billions of dollars to foreigners in exchange for 
imported goods 
that means that foreigners now own more in us investments than 
americans own in overseas investments the question of the 
willingness of foreign investors to continue holding us 
investments is likely to be the biggest economic problem facing 
presidentelect bush 
the dollar fell sharply in the days following bushs election as 
investors feared his notax pledge and the larger democratic 
majorities in congress would mean a continuation of the sevenyear 
budget deadlock to reassure jittery markets bush has taken to 
pledging at every opportunity that he views tackling the budget 
deficit as his top priority 
at the end of last year americas net debt had grown to 3682 
billion and many economists believe the current accounts 
performance this year will push the net debt level above 500 
billion by the end of 1988 
some economists have warned that the debt service burden will 
eventually lower americans standard of living by reducing the 
amount of money available in this country for government operations 
business investment and individual consumption 
the reagan administration has sought to play down the 
significance of the countrys net debtor status saying that the 
cost of financing that debt is still a tiny fraction of the 
countrys 5 trillion economy 
economists said however that the deficit in the services 
category in the second quarter although small was an ominous 
event before 1982 america was able to count on surpluses from its 
overseas investment earnings to erase perennial merchandise trade 
deficits 
but with foreigners now holding a bigger share of us 
investments the country will never be able to eliminate its current 
account deficit unless it starts running surpluses in the 
merchandise category something that even optimistic forecasters say 
will be impossible until well into the next decade 
for that reason some economists have forecast that the level of 
the countrys net debtor position will approach 1 trillion before 
it starts to show any improvement 
for the third quarter the deficit in merchandise trade declined 
to 2853 billion its third consecutive quarterly improvement 
added to this figure was an increase to 312 billion in us 
foreign aid and pension payments overseas 
the small 757 million surplus in investments and other services 
is subtracted from those deficit figures to arrive at the current 
account deficit of 3089 billion 
many economists fear that the improvement in the trade deficit 
this year which has accounted for almost half of the overall growth 
in the economy is in danger of stalling next year without a major 
push by the bush administration to open up foreign markets and 
without further declines in the value of the dollar 
the national association of manufacturers issued a report today 
calling on the bush administration to move aggressively to use the 
powers in the new trade bill to open foreign markets 
weve made significant advances toward reducing the us trade 
deficit but unless policymakers cooperate we face the danger of a 
midpoint stall and a large trade deficit that will continue to 
plague us far into the next decade said jerry jasinowski 
executive vice president of the manufacturers group 
</TEXT>
