<TEXT>
the us economy is likely to do better in 1989 
than it has this year because of growth in exports and capital 
spending the nations purchasing managers said in a report released 
tuesday 
fiftythree percent of the purchasing managers surveyed felt 
their businesses would be better in 1989 than in 1988 compared with 
13 percent who expected it would be worse the national association 
of purchasing management said the rest thought it would be about 
the same 
the report is based on a survey of purchasing executives in more 
than 250 industrial companies in all 50 states 
the exceptionally high level of optimism expressed by 
purchasing managers about the next 12 months overshadows their 
concerns regarding inflation rising interest rates and the budget 
deficit robert j bretz chairman of the associations business 
survey committee and director of materials management at pitney 
bowes inc said in a written statement 
overall theyre expecting a continuation of a very healthy 
growth throughout all of 1989 perhaps heavier in the first half 
than the last half bretz said in an interview 
on inflation 87 percent predicted their companies would be 
paying higher prices at the end of 1989 than at the end of 1988 and 
of those the average inflation forecast was 42 percent seven 
percent predicted lower prices with an average forecast decline of 
24 percent 
the association said the combination of answers on inflation 
translated into a prediction of a net average price increase of 37 
percent in 1989 the managers expect a net average price increase of 
5 percent for this year 
members reported their companies were operating at the highest 
percentage of capacity since may 1979 the 76 percent who said 1988 
fully measured up to their expectations was the most to say so since 
1978 
the top three concerns mentioned by the purchasing managers were 
inflation cited cited by 22 percent rising interest rates 14 
percent and the federal budget deficit 13 percent 
on capital expenditures 42 percent said they expected to spend 
more in 1989 while 24 percent said they expected to spend less 
asked a broader question about the outlook for the economy in 
general not just their own companies 48 percent said they were 
satisfied or optimistic the highest reading for a december survey 
since december 1983 
fifty percent said they were concerned and 2 percent said they 
were worried or pessimistic 
