atari games corps doublebarreled attack 
on nintendo co could be the opening zaps of a broader battle in the 
multibilliondollar home video game market 
at issue is whether nintendo the leading maker of video game 
machines can control the software market by limiting the number of 
games it makes under licensing agreements with software developers 
and preventing them from making the games independently 
atari games a licensee says nintendo is violating antimonopoly 
laws and has sued for 100 million in damages 
but mediagenic another licensee formerly called activision says 
nintendos controls may be illegal but probably are good for the 
market overall 
nintendo a japanese company with a us subsidiary based in 
redmond wash isnt saying what it thinks although its attorneys 
are studying the lawsuit atari games filed against it monday in us 
district court in san francisco 
nintendo which controls 80 percent of the us market for home 
video game machines may be planning a countersuit to stop atari 
games from releasing through its tengen inc software subsidiary the 
first independently manufactured video game cartridges for nintendo 
machines 
atari games a privatelyheld company based in milpitas calif 
and unrelated to computermaker atari inc claims its profits have 
been hurt because it is required to turn to nintendo for 
manufacturing and is limited in the number of cartridges it may sell 
we have been able to get only a small fraction of the games we 
want to sell into the market said dennis wood senior vice 
president for atari games we are so frustrated by our inability 
to get the proper supplies 
atari games says nintendo has equipped its machines with a 
computer chip that allows them to accept only video game cartridges 
with a compatible chip 
using this barrier and its completely dominating position in 
the market for home video game machines nintendo has forced the 
more than 30 companies that have written games that play on nintendo 
machines to have all of their game cartridges manufactured by 
nintendojapan at prices it dictates the suit states 
the suit claims atari games lost between 30 million and 35 
million because of inadequate supplies atari games is seeking three 
times its direct losses under the provision for treble damages in 
antimonopoly suits 
ataris tengen subsidiary has about 35 million in annual sales 
nintendo in recent years has cashed in on what some have 
described as an almost cultlike consumer devotion to its games the 
company reported 800 million in sales last year and expects to more 
than double that this year 
bruce davis president of mediagenic based in mountain view 
says nintendo has maintained its restrictive licensing procedure in 
a principled way 
they dont give anyone as much product as they want and they 
give some more than others but that have a rationale for what 
theyre doing said davis whose companies sells two 
nintendolicensed games super pitfall and ghostbusters 
davis was in redmond on monday to negotiate licenses for several 
new products 
nintendo is trying to control quality and overall inventory he 
said two areas that led to the collapse of the video game industry 
in the early 1980s after astonishing growth in the 1970s 
activision and atari were two of the biggest losers in the 
collapse atari games and atari inidiary foundered and eventually 
was sold and dividedwarner subsidiary foundered and eventually was 
sold and divided 
davis said mediagenic which posted 26 million in sales and 
500000 in profits in the first six months this fiscal year could 
have sold more nintendobased products if it were allowed 
but i cant complain the way nintendo has conducted business 
given the licensing arrangement he said i would prefer not to 
pay a licensing fee or to have them be the sole source manufacturer 
but i dont think its in our interest now to challenge it 
